{"parentUuid":"3e12dc40-9d23-4cec-927c-28282bdda602","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a98d53b8f2a71429f","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:WebSearch","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01AoqW6QWAwRv1i3MhwRahTQ","toolUseID":"toolu_01AoqW6QWAwRv1i3MhwRahTQ","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:18:37.011Z","uuid":"4def074f-97ef-4f87-947d-f577670004af","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"6e9e230f-ea4b-4883-a144-b4a61e553440","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"a98d53b8f2a71429f","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AoqW6QWAwRv1i3MhwRahTQ","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Wikipedia language spawning model how new wikis are created governance\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"List of Wikipedias - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Wikipedias\"},{\"title\":\"Wikipedia's value in the age of generative AI – Wikimedia Foundation\",\"url\":\"https://wikimediafoundation.org/news/2023/07/12/wikipedias-value-in-the-age-of-generative-ai/\"},{\"title\":\"Wiki - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiki\"},{\"title\":\"Content translation tool helps create over half a million Wikipedia articles – Wikimedia Foundation\",\"url\":\"https://wikimediafoundation.org/news/2019/09/23/content-translation-tool-helps-create-over-half-a-million-wikipedia-articles/\"},{\"title\":\"How Wikipedia editors collaborate on article \\\"talk\\\" pages\",\"url\":\"https://huskiecommons.lib.niu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=4415&context=allgraduate-thesesdissertations\"},{\"title\":\"Wikipedia’s value in the age of generative AI | by Selena Deckelmann | Down the Rabbit Hole | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/freely-sharing-the-sum-of-all-knowledge/wikipedias-value-in-the-age-of-generative-ai-b19fec06bbee\"},{\"title\":\"What programming language is Wikipedia made in? - Quora\",\"url\":\"https://www.quora.com/What-programming-language-is-Wikipedia-made-in\"},{\"title\":\"Wikipedia:Large language models - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Large_language_models\"},{\"title\":\"List of Wikipedias - Meta-Wiki\",\"url\":\"https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/List_of_Wikipedias\"},{\"title\":\"Wiki | Definition & Facts | Britannica\",\"url\":\"https://www.britannica.com/topic/wiki\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Wikipedia's language spawning model and how new wikis are created:\n\n## Governance and Requirements for New Wikis\n\nThe Meta-Wiki language committee manages policies on creating new Wikimedia projects. To be eligible, a language must have a valid ISO 639 code, be \"sufficiently unique\", and have a \"sufficient number of fluent users\".\n\n## Creating New Language Versions\n\nTo start a Wikipedia in a new language, there is a language proposal policy and the Incubator manual that guide the process. The Wikimedia Incubator is where new language versions (known as \"tests\") may become stand-alone wikis in the future.\n\n## Current Wikipedia Editions\n\nAs of March 2026, Wikipedia articles have been created in 361 editions, with 345 currently active, 16 closed and 11 moved to Incubator. This shows that the model allows for the expansion of Wikipedia into new languages, with a testing phase in the Incubator before becoming active projects.\n\n## Handling Language Variants\n\nThe model also includes flexibility in how language variants are handled. Wikipedia projects vary in how they divide dialects and variants. For example, the English Wikipedia includes most modern varieties of English including American English and British English. Similarly, the Catalan Wikipedia encompasses all Catalan variants, like Valencian, Balearic or France's Catalan.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"9cd28ab6-9021-4d89-aad2-557f19227e88","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:18:37.011Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"6e9e230f-ea4b-4883-a144-b4a61e553440","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"9cd28ab6-9021-4d89-aad2-557f19227e88","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a98d53b8f2a71429f","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:WebSearch","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01V2b3zNyVRhdx8bMjnzZEMH","toolUseID":"toolu_01V2b3zNyVRhdx8bMjnzZEMH","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:18:37.539Z","uuid":"33354407-8b6f-4406-b12d-604deb9dc978","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"b86384cf-a5a1-4c09-b0b1-b6e4bd8d6b9a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"a98d53b8f2a71429f","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01V2b3zNyVRhdx8bMjnzZEMH","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"WordPress Multisite architecture how one codebase serves millions of sites\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"WordPress Multisite, a Decision Guide | Pantheon.io\",\"url\":\"https://pantheon.io/multisite-wordpress\"},{\"title\":\"WordPress Multisite Explained: Pros, Cons, and Best Practices - Codeable\",\"url\":\"https://www.codeable.io/blog/wordpress-multisite-development/\"},{\"title\":\"7 WordPress Multisite Examples From Leading Brands\",\"url\":\"https://www.multidots.com/blog/wordpress-multisite-examples/\"},{\"title\":\"WordPress Multisite vs Single Site – Which Fits Your Needs?\",\"url\":\"https://www.multidots.com/blog/wordpress-multisite-vs-single-site/\"},{\"title\":\"WordPress Multisite: Complete Guide - IT Monks Agency\",\"url\":\"https://itmonks.com/blog/wp-development/multisite/\"},{\"title\":\"WordPress Multisite Explained From Architecture to Implementation | Pantheon.io\",\"url\":\"https://pantheon.io/learning-center/wordpress/multisite\"},{\"title\":\"WordPress Multisite Setup and Configuration Tutorial | Pantheon.io\",\"url\":\"https://pantheon.io/learning-center/wordpress/multisite-setup\"},{\"title\":\"A Guide to Scaling WordPress Multisite 2026 | development | WPPoland\",\"url\":\"https://wppoland.com/en/managing-100-websites-wordpress-multisite-2026-en/\"},{\"title\":\"The Ultimate Guide to Understanding and Mastering WordPress Multisite - Convesio Knowledge Base\",\"url\":\"https://convesio.com/knowledgebase/article/the-ultimate-guide-to-understanding-and-mastering-wordpress-multisite/\"},{\"title\":\"WordPress Multisite Setup Guide with Use Cases and Pitfalls\",\"url\":\"https://www.arhpez.com/blogs/wordpress-multisite-architecture-setup-use-cases-and-common-pitfalls/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's a comprehensive overview of WordPress Multisite architecture and how it serves millions of sites:\n\n## Core Architecture\n\nWordPress Multisite is a feature that allows you to manage multiple WordPress websites from a single WordPress installation, where you create a network sharing the same core files, themes, and plugins instead of separate installations for each site.\n\nThe database structure is optimized for multiple sites, using shared tables for users, plugins, and some settings, while maintaining separate tables for each site's content and options, allowing for efficient data management and keeping individual site content isolated.\n\n## How One Codebase Serves Multiple Sites\n\nOne codebase serves your entire network by sharing WordPress core files, themes, and plugins across all sites, dramatically reducing server overhead and hosting costs.\n\nUpdates to WordPress core, themes, and plugins are applied once and automatically extend across every site, ensuring security and consistency without adding workload for IT.\n\n## Real-World Scale Examples\n\nThe architecture proves capable of handling massive scale: WordPress.com, which powers all of its users' sites with a single installation of WordPress, includes 160 million users among companies like Samsung, TIME, Salesforce, Aljazeera, and Abercrombie & Fitch.\n\nAsk Media uses WordPress Multisite to manage 11 high-traffic properties serving 245 million monthly visitors. Additionally, Harvard Blogs runs 10,000+ academic sites on one Multisite network.\n\n## Performance Scaling for Large Networks\n\nAt scale you'll need Redis for object caching, database sharding once you pass 500 sites, and CDN integration for media across regions. In 2026, with object caching (Redis) and database sharding, a Multisite setup can be faster and more efficient to host than 100 separate small sites.\n\nThis architecture represents a powerful solution for organizations managing multiple related sites efficiently from a centralized platform.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"ca139d45-764a-4f44-9eb3-cc34201a8309","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:18:37.539Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b86384cf-a5a1-4c09-b0b1-b6e4bd8d6b9a","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
